Forget about grand gestures and bold declarations of love. Real intimacy can be found in the smallest moments of everyday life. A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Mar 21, 2015 at 7:16am PDT Young Ju Kim, an illustrator and toy designer based in Seoul, South Korea, captures this beautifully in his ongoing series “Soso and Haru.” “I wanted to express the love of ordinary people,” he told HuffPost. “I sometimes draw my experience and I also observe and draw the love of people around me.” Soso and Haru’s everyday adventures in love include a nighttime stroll through the city: A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Apr 10, 2015 at 8:48am PDT And an impromptu dance party: A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Jan 20, 2018 at 4:00am PST And just cuddling while watching a show on their laptop: A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Jan 25, 2015 at 3:50am PST Kim, who is currently single, began the series in 2014 but didn’t name the characters until the following year. Their names come from the Korean phrase “sosohan haru,” which means a typical, ordinary day. A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Jun 3, 2016 at 5:04pm PDT A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Apr 13, 2015 at 9:03pm PDT The adorable drawings are predominantly black and white with small pops of color. “I wanted to express the feeling of memories of the past,” Kim said. “The happy days are white, the sad days are black, and daily life is expressed in gray with a mixture of joy and sorrow.” See more of Kim’s illustrations below. You can follow the artist on Instagram or Facebook, or visit his Grafolio page. A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Nov 28, 2015 at 4:48am PST A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Aug 5, 2016 at 4:08am PDT A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Nov 10, 2015 at 5:57pm PST A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Sep 14, 2016 at 4:56pm PDT A post shared by Kim Youngju (@ingyoungjoo) on Nov 2, 2015 at